:::summary
Delphi was the most sacred site in the ancient Greek world — home to the Oracle of Apollo, whose pronouncements guided kings, generals, and city-states for nearly a thousand years. Perched on the slopes of Mount Parnassus, Delphi was believed by the Greeks to be the *omphalos* — the navel of the world. Its maxims, including "Know thyself," shaped Greek culture and philosophy in profound ways.
:::

